id="post-3673" class="post-3673 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-politics tag-car tag-chengdu tag-china tag-sustainable tag-urban"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2013/02/21/china-to-build-car-free-city/" title="Permalink to China to Build Car-Free City" rel="bookmark">China to Build Car-Free City</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2013/02/21 10:25 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2013/02/21/china-to-build-car-free-city/" title="China to Build Car-Free City" rel="bookmark">2013/02/21 10:25 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p><img
src="http://i2.wp.com/img.weburbanist.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Carless-City-China-5.jpg?w=520" alt="" data-recalc-dims="1" /></p><p>The Chinese city of Chengdu will be getting a new neighbour, an entire city purpose built city for people instead of cars. China&#8217;s capital city Beijing is known for its smog problems and the Chinese government is under more and more pressure to implement environmentally-friendly policies. Creating sustainable urban centres are a step in the right direction.</p><blockquote><p>Chicago architecture firm Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture say the city will use 48% less energy and 58% less water than a more conventional city of the same size; it will also produce 89% less landfill waste and generate 60% less carbon dioxide.<br
/> &#8230;<br
/> “Accordingly, we’ve designed this project as a dense vertical city that acknowledges and in fact embraces the surrounding landscape—a city whose residents will live in harmony with nature rather than in opposition to it. Great City will demonstrate that high-density living doesn’t have to be polluted and alienated from nature. Everything within the built environment of Great City is considered to enhance the quality of life of its residents. Quite simply, it offers a great place to live, work and raise a family.”</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://weburbanist.com/2013/02/11/car-free-city-china-builds-dense-metropolis-from-scratch/">Read more at WebUrbanist</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-3673-5383a0321d188' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=3673&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-3673-5383a0321d188' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-3673-5383a0321d188'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
