id="post-3357" class="post-3357 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-direct-action category-equality category-freedom category-technology tag-c-30 tag-canada tag-china tag-community tag-internet tag-net-neutrality tag-sopa tag-usa"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2012/07/04/declaration-of-internet-freedom/" title="Permalink to Declaration of Internet Freedom" rel="bookmark">Declaration of Internet Freedom</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2012/07/04 10:10 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2012/07/04/declaration-of-internet-freedom/" title="Declaration of Internet Freedom" rel="bookmark">2012/07/04 10:10 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Around the world governments are trying to restrain the ability of people to freely share information across the internet. Bills like SOPA in the USA and Bill C-30 in Canada to the more recent TPP all focus on propping up old media monopolies and curtailing people&#8217;s privacy and communication rights. The most effective and extreme example of clamping down on the internet can be seen in the Great Firewall of China.</p><p>WIth the above in mind, it&#8217;s good to see that a group of people have taken up the challenge of creating a universal declaration of freedom for online access and participation!</p><p>The Preamble:</p><blockquote><p>We believe that a free and open Internet can bring about a better world. To keep the Internet free and open, we call on communities, industries and countries to recognize these principles. We believe that they will help to bring about more creativity, more innovation and more open societies.</p><p>We are joining an international movement to defend our freedoms because we believe that they are worth fighting for.</p><p>Let’s discuss these principles — agree or disagree with them, debate them, translate them, make them your own and broaden the discussion with your community — as only the Internet can make possible.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.internetdeclaration.org/freedom">Go to the Declaration of Internet Freedom</a>.</p><p><a
href="http://openmedia.ca/">Canadians please check out OpenMedia.</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-3357-5383a0321eaee' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=3357&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-3357-5383a0321eaee' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-3357-5383a0321eaee'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
